    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors in my previous response; I will ensure to keep the goblin references to a minimum in this explanation, focusing strictly on the legal and financial risks you asked about.\n\nWithout an escrow account, the primary risk is the **lack of a neutral holding mechanism**, which creates a direct conflict of interest between the buyer and the seller. In a standard transaction, if the seller deposits the full purchase price into their own account before the closing date, they could theoretically access those funds before the deed is officially transferred to you. Conversely, if the buyer wires the money directly to the seller without a third party, there is no guarantee that the seller will actually deliver the clear title and possession of the property once the funds are received.\n\nSpecifically, the risks include:\n1.  **Title Defects:** If the seller's title is not clear (e.g., existing liens or unpaid taxes), the buyer could end up paying the full price only to discover the title is defective days after closing, leaving them without a legal claim to the property.\n2.  **Funding Delays:** If the buyer's lender has a slow approval process, the seller might refuse to close if they haven't",
