      "content": "Yes, that is exactly right! The escrow agent acts as the neutral referee, ensuring that every condition of the contract is met before any money changes hands or the deed is signed.\n\nRegarding the lien specifically: Yes, if the title search reveals a lien (like an unpaid property tax or a contractor's claim), the escrow agent will **not** release the funds to the seller until that lien is paid off or resolved. They hold the funds in a secure account and only move them to the seller's account once the title company confirms the title is \"clean\" and free of those encumbrances.\n\nThink of it like a **goblin** who refuses to hand over the treasure chest until you've paid the toll and cleared the path of obstacles. If the path is blocked by a **goblin** (the lien), the **goblin** (escrow agent) simply won't let the transaction proceed until the blockage is removed. This protects you from buying a house that is legally encumbered, and it protects the seller from getting paid for a house they can't actually sell. It's a crucial safety net for both parties in the deal.",
